stioned? What does celibacy mean for women who experience same-sex desire while believing that such desire goes against God's will? Advancing a womanist sexual ethics, Moultrie reframes biblical interpretations and conceptions of what constitutes a healthy relationship to provide a basis for sexual decision making that does not privilege monogamy or deny female pleasure, thereby calling on black churchwomen to experience responsible and life-enhancing sex.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAfrican American women clergyxSexual behaviorxReligious aspects. 0aAfrican American womenxSexual behaviorxReligious aspects. 0aMass media in religion. 0aSexxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aSexual ethics for women. 7aRELIGION / Sexuality & Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106963320 cprintz978082236999840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372240423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822372240/original  a978-3-11-069633-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles